{"name":"Dose the Tin Man - The Giant in Love","type":"npc","img":"icons/equipment/chest/breastplate-banded-steel.webp","system":{"npcType":"creature","oppositionLevel":5,"isMainNPC":true,"background":"Dose suffers from leprosy and other contagious diseases. In early 1900s America, to protect others from infection, he made the agonizing decision to seal himself inside crude metal armor—plates bolted and strapped onto his body, covering him completely except for a small door over his heart. The armor protected others but isolated him completely. He could no longer feel anything through the metal—no warmth, no gentle touch, no human contact. Over time, he began to fear he was becoming hollow inside, losing his humanity piece by piece, transforming into nothing but empty metal. When the Compass Rose threw him to 1780, Dose found himself in a world where his appearance—a walking metal man—terrified villagers who thought him a demon or golem. He follows Dorothea because she accepts him despite his armor, and because protecting her gives meaning to his hollowness. His voice is muffled and echoing through his helmet. His movements are stiff and mechanical. He constantly adjusts his armor, a nervous habit from years of maintaining the seal. Dose desperately wants to feel something—anything—again. In Part Three, if he survives, Dose experiences the most dramatic transformation: he falls in love with a villager of Smaragd. The power of that love begins to physically transform him. Where his beloved touches his armor, it falls away and living flesh grows in its place. Dose the Giant in Love still retains metal armor over most of his body (providing immunity to physical attacks), but patches of exposed flesh show on his arms, chest, and face. The area around his heart—his most vulnerable spot—is now unprotected flesh, covered only by the small door. When fighting to protect his beloved, Dose can act twice in one Exchange, love giving him superhuman determination. His movements become more fluid, more human. He speaks constantly about his beloved, showing emotion rather than mechanical detachment.","descriptors":["I suffer from leprosy encased in metal armor to protect others from contagion","I cannot feel anything through the metal and fear I'm becoming hollow inside","I desperately want to feel human connection again but armor keeps me isolated","By Part Three: I've fallen in love and my armor is being replaced by living flesh where love touches"],"agenda":["Protect my companions who accept me despite my armor","Find a cure so I can feel again and be truly human","Prevent myself from becoming completely hollow—a monster without humanity","In Part Three: Protect my beloved at any cost and embrace my returning humanity"],"attributes":{"soma":{"current":0,"max":0},"wounds":{"current":0,"max":3,"extra":{"value":0,"max":1}}},"gifts":[{"name":"Of Steel (Parts One and Two)","description":"Dose's entire body (except for a small door over his heart) is covered in crude metal armor bolted and strapped onto him. He is immune to ALL physical attacks (swords, arrows, blunt force, etc.) unless: An attacker specifically targets the heart door, which requires spending 1 Increment from their Outcome to aim precisely, OR the attack is magical or supernatural in nature (fire, lightning, curses, etc.). When the heart door is opened or successfully targeted, Dose loses this immunity for the rest of the Scene, as the impact disrupts the armor's integrity. His armor makes him nearly invincible to mundane weapons but creates a critical vulnerability.","somaCost":0},{"name":"Giant","description":"Dose has 1 additional Wound beyond what his importance would normally grant (giving him 3 Wounds total plus 1 extra Wound for 4 total). His massive armored form and enhanced endurance make him extraordinarily difficult to bring down.","somaCost":0},{"name":"Of Steel and Love (Part Three Transformation)","description":"**ONLY IN PART THREE:** Dose's armor is slowly being replaced by living flesh wherever his beloved touches him. **Partial Immunity:** Dose still has metal armor covering most of his body, providing immunity to physical attacks except where flesh is exposed (face, arms, chest patches). **Vulnerable Heart:** The area around his heart is now unprotected flesh covered only by the small door. Attacking this spot requires 1 Increment but completely bypasses his armor immunity. **Love's Strength:** When fighting to protect his beloved, Dose can act twice in one Exchange instead of once, empowered by desperate love and the return of human emotion.","somaCost":0}],"conditions":[],"specialNotes":"Dose is the Tin Man seeking a heart—but discovers he had one all along when he finds love. Roleplaying notes: Voice muffled and echoing through helmet, speaks about wanting to feel things; movements stiff and mechanical in Parts One/Two, becomes more fluid in Part Three; constantly adjusts armor (nervous habit); in Part Three shows patches of exposed flesh and speaks constantly about beloved with emotion and wonder. Key transformation moment: when beloved first touches his face and armor falls away revealing human skin, Dose weeps for first time in years—can finally feel tears. If Hunters show him compassion (acknowledging his sacrifice to protect others through isolation), he's deeply moved and may refuse to fight them later. If treated as just a monster or obstacle, he fights mechanically without emotion. His tragedy: he voluntarily imprisoned himself in armor out of selfless desire to protect others from disease, but that protection cost him his humanity. His redemption: love literally brings his humanity back, flesh replacing metal where love touches. Ultimate fate: if he survives and is redeemed, he chooses to stay in 1780 with his beloved, watching the last pieces of armor fall away as he becomes fully human again. If killed, his final words are about wishing he could have felt one more time. The small heart door can be recovered as tragic memento—symbol of his vulnerability and humanity."},"_id":"0313e97983d36e96"}
{"name":"Hirnloser the Scarecrow - The Genius","type":"npc","img":"icons/equipment/head/hood-cowl-worn-tan.webp","system":{"npcType":"creature","oppositionLevel":5,"isMainNPC":true,"background":"Hirnloser was a psychiatric patient in early 1900s America. The doctors diagnosed him as mentally ill, saying his brain didn't work correctly. After years of being told he was mad and broken, Hirnloser came to believe he literally had no brain at all—a delusion that paradoxically freed his mind. In the asylum, he developed an unusual way of perceiving the world, seeing patterns and truths that others missed beneath surface appearances. When thrown back to 1780 by the Compass Rose malfunction, Hirnloser found himself in a world that didn't understand mental illness any better than his own time. He attached himself to Dorothea because she, unlike the doctors, gave him purpose instead of just dismissing him as insane. Hirnloser moves in jerky, unsettling ways like a scarecrow animated by magic. He speaks in riddles, rhymes, and fragmented sentences that seem nonsensical but often contain profound insights. Despite his madness (or because of it), he perceives truths others cannot: he knows Henkle is manipulating them, understands that the witches aren't actually evil, and sees the larger patterns of their situation. But his fractured communication makes it nearly impossible for others to understand his warnings. Throughout the campaign, Hirnloser undergoes transformation. By Part Three, if he survives and experiences the truth being validated, he becomes Hirnloser the Genius. His speech clears, becoming precise and brilliant. He realizes his mind was never broken—it was extraordinary, seeing connections others couldn't. As The Genius, he provides tactical insights, prepares countermeasures, and always has the right tool. His Gift allows him to prevent Hunter Gifts through explanation, describe tactics that automatically succeed, and be prepared for any situation. His arc represents society's failure to recognize neurodivergent brilliance.","descriptors":["I am a psychiatric patient from early 1900s—they said I was mad, that my brain didn't work right","Now I believe I have no brain at all, but I see things others cannot","I speak in riddles and move like a scarecrow, but I perceive the truth beneath surfaces","By Part Three, I realize my mind is my greatest weapon—I am a genius"],"agenda":["Follow OZena because she gives me purpose and doesn't dismiss me as just 'mad'","Understand the truth of this strange world we're trapped in","Prove I'm more than the madman they say I am","In Part Three: Use my brilliant mind to help or hinder the Hunters"],"attributes":{"soma":{"current":0,"max":0},"wounds":{"current":0,"max":3,"extra":{"value":0,"max":0}}},"gifts":[{"name":"Genius (Part Three Transformation)","description":"**ONLY IN PART THREE:** Hirnloser has realized his intellect is extraordinary. **Tactical Insight:** Once per Scene, Hirnloser can describe a brilliant tactic or strategy that automatically succeeds without requiring a Check. This could be identifying a weakness, setting a perfect ambush, or solving a complex problem instantly. **Countermeasure:** Three times per Scene, Hirnloser can prevent a Hunter from activating a Gift by rapidly explaining how to counter it, neutralizing the advantage. **Prepared:** Hirnloser always has the right tool, item, or piece of information for the current situation, as if he anticipated it. His transformation into The Genius represents validation that his mind was never broken—just different and more advanced than those who judged him.","somaCost":0}],"conditions":[],"specialNotes":"Hirnloser is the truth-teller whose madness makes him hard to understand. In Parts One and Two: speaks only in riddles and rhymes; movements are jerky and unsettling, tilts head at odd angles; stares intensely at things others don't notice; his riddles contain actual truth if decoded (example: 'The scarecrow sees what you cannot. The tin man feels nothing but knows everything. The lion roars but runs away. And the girl with silver shoes walks the yellow road to death' = warning about OZena's path to destruction). If captured by Hunters, he reveals important truths in riddles: 'The wizard in emerald is not what he seems. He steals what he cannot create. The rose blooms red with blood.' In Part Three transformation: speech becomes clear, precise, analytical; shows pride in his intellect; rapidly analyzes situations; no longer rhymes or speaks cryptically. Key moment: when his 'mad' warnings are proven correct, he has breakthrough realization that he was never insane—society just couldn't understand his brilliance. If Hunters show him respect and try to decode his riddles, he becomes more coherent and may help them. If dismissed as 'just crazy,' he becomes hostile, bitter that even in fairy tale world he's not believed. Ultimate fate: may stay in 1780 to become true inventor/scholar or return to revolutionize early 1900s psychiatry with insights about neurodivergent minds."},"_id":"28b92d5a41b4c578"}
{"name":"Lowe the Coward - The Brave Fighter","type":"npc","img":"icons/creatures/mammals/lion-humanoid-roar.webp","system":{"npcType":"creature","oppositionLevel":5,"isMainNPC":true,"background":"Lowe suffers from leontiasis, a rare disease that causes his facial bones to grow abnormally, making his face resemble a lion's. In early 1900s America, he was mocked, feared, and called a coward because he learned to adapt and survive by siding with whoever held power. When Dr. Henkle's Compass Rose malfunctioned and threw them to 1780, Lowe found himself in a world where his appearance was even more terrifying to superstitious villagers. He follows Dorothea (OZena) because she gives him purpose and companionship—she doesn't judge his appearance or his survival tactics. Lowe is actually the most rational of OZena's three companions. He questions her increasingly violent methods but fears abandoning her would mean losing the only family he has. He's not evil—he's pragmatic. He'll side with whoever is winning because that's how he's learned to survive. But deep down, he wishes he had the courage to stand up for what's right rather than what's safe. Throughout the campaign, Lowe undergoes character development. If the Hunters show him kindness and understanding, he begins to question Henkle's manipulation. By Part Three, he can transform into Lowe the Brave Fighter—a lion-faced warrior who has finally found his courage. He becomes immune to fear, inspires allies, and stands firm even when outmatched. His cowardice was never weakness—it was survival. When he finally finds something worth fighting for (whether OZena's redemption or stopping Henkle's madness), he becomes truly heroic. If the Hunters treat him with contempt or violence, he remains hostile and defensive, convinced they're no better than the witch hunters of the 18th century.","descriptors":["I suffer from leontiasis, a disease that makes my face look like a lion's","People call me a coward because I adapt to survive—I'll side with whoever is winning","I just want to belong somewhere and protect those who accept me","I'm more rational than my companions but too afraid to speak up"],"agenda":["Survive and get home to my own time","Protect my companions Dorothea, Hirnloser, and Dose","Avoid unnecessary violence when possible","Find the courage to do what's right instead of what's safe"],"attributes":{"soma":{"current":0,"max":0},"wounds":{"current":0,"max":2,"extra":{"value":0,"max":0}}},"gifts":[{"name":"Hero (Part Three Transformation)","description":"**ONLY IN PART THREE:** Lowe has overcome his cowardice and embraced heroism. **Fearless:** Lowe is immune to all fear effects, intimidation, and mind control attempts. **Inspiring Presence:** Allied NPCs within 30 feet of Lowe gain +1 to their Opposition Level, emboldened by his courage. **Last Stand:** When reduced to 0 Wounds, Lowe can take one final action before falling—a dramatic last strike, final words, or heroic sacrifice. His transformation into The Brave Fighter represents finding something worth fighting for regardless of the odds.","somaCost":0}],"conditions":[],"specialNotes":"Lowe is a tragic figure who represents survival versus heroism. In Parts One and Two, he's conflicted—observes Hunters from distance in Part One to assess if they're threats or potential allies; may negotiate in swamp encounter if Hunters were kind to Henrich and Klaus; attacks alongside OZena in Part Two if she's hostile, but hesitates if shown evidence of Henkle's lies. Voice is hesitant and apologetic initially, becomes more confident in Part Three. Mannerisms: avoids direct eye contact initially, keeps distance, ready to flee; in Part Three stands tall, meets eyes directly, protective stance. Key moment: if Hunters show compassion for his condition rather than disgust, he gains respect for them and is more likely to negotiate or even betray Henkle. If OZena is killed or captured in Part Two and Lowe blames the Hunters, he becomes hostile in Part Three, viewing them as murderers. His ultimate fate: if redeemed, he may stay in 1780 to live boldly or return home to revolutionize treatment of disfigured people; if killed, his last words thank someone for treating him with dignity. Storytellers should emphasize that his 'cowardice' was intelligent survival—he adapted because that's how outcasts survive in cruel worlds."},"_id":"b8b4a3c179b16508"}
{"name":"Dose the Tin Man - The Giant in Love","type":"npc","img":"icons/equipment/chest/breastplate-banded-steel.webp","system":{"npcType":"creature","oppositionLevel":5,"isMainNPC":true,"background":"Dose suffers from leprosy and other contagious diseases. In early 1900s America, to protect others from infection, he made the agonizing decision to seal himself inside crude metal armor—plates bolted and strapped onto his body, covering him completely except for a small door over his heart. The armor protected others but isolated him completely. He could no longer feel anything through the metal—no warmth, no gentle touch, no human contact. Over time, he began to fear he was becoming hollow inside, losing his humanity piece by piece, transforming into nothing but empty metal. When the Compass Rose threw him to 1780, Dose found himself in a world where his appearance—a walking metal man—terrified villagers who thought him a demon or golem. He follows Dorothea because she accepts him despite his armor, and because protecting her gives meaning to his hollowness. His voice is muffled and echoing through his helmet. His movements are stiff and mechanical. He constantly adjusts his armor, a nervous habit from years of maintaining the seal. Dose desperately wants to feel something—anything—again. In Part Three, if he survives, Dose experiences the most dramatic transformation: he falls in love with a villager of Smaragd. The power of that love begins to physically transform him. Where his beloved touches his armor, it falls away and living flesh grows in its place. Dose the Giant in Love still retains metal armor over most of his body (providing immunity to physical attacks), but patches of exposed flesh show on his arms, chest, and face. The area around his heart—his most vulnerable spot—is now unprotected flesh, covered only by the small door. When fighting to protect his beloved, Dose can act twice in one Exchange, love giving him superhuman determination. His movements become more fluid, more human. He speaks constantly about his beloved, showing emotion rather than mechanical detachment.","descriptors":["I suffer from leprosy encased in metal armor to protect others from contagion","I cannot feel anything through the metal and fear I'm becoming hollow inside","I desperately want to feel human connection again but armor keeps me isolated","By Part Three: I've fallen in love and my armor is being replaced by living flesh where love touches"],"agenda":["Protect my companions who accept me despite my armor","Find a cure so I can feel again and be truly human","Prevent myself from becoming completely hollow—a monster without humanity","In Part Three: Protect my beloved at any cost and embrace my returning humanity"],"attributes":{"soma":{"current":0,"max":0},"wounds":{"current":0,"max":3,"extra":{"value":0,"max":1}}},"gifts":[{"name":"Of Steel (Parts One and Two)","description":"Dose's entire body (except for a small door over his heart) is covered in crude metal armor bolted and strapped onto him. He is immune to ALL physical attacks (swords, arrows, blunt force, etc.) unless: An attacker specifically targets the heart door, which requires spending 1 Increment from their Outcome to aim precisely, OR the attack is magical or supernatural in nature (fire, lightning, curses, etc.). When the heart door is opened or successfully targeted, Dose loses this immunity for the rest of the Scene, as the impact disrupts the armor's integrity. His armor makes him nearly invincible to mundane weapons but creates a critical vulnerability.","somaCost":0},{"name":"Giant","description":"Dose has 1 additional Wound beyond what his importance would normally grant (giving him 3 Wounds total plus 1 extra Wound for 4 total). His massive armored form and enhanced endurance make him extraordinarily difficult to bring down.","somaCost":0},{"name":"Of Steel and Love (Part Three Transformation)","description":"**ONLY IN PART THREE:** Dose's armor is slowly being