nts society's failure to recognize neurodivergent brilliance.","descriptors":["I am a psychiatric patient from early 1900s—they said I was mad, that my brain didn't work right","Now I believe I have no brain at all, but I see things others cannot","I speak in riddles and move like a scarecrow, but I perceive the truth beneath surfaces","By Part Three, I realize my mind is my greatest weapon—I am a genius"],"agenda":["Follow OZena because she gives me purpose and doesn't dismiss me as just 'mad'","Understand the truth of this strange world we're trapped in","Prove I'm more than the madman they say I am","In Part Three: Use my brilliant mind to help or hinder the Hunters"],"attributes":{"soma":{"current":0,"max":0},"wounds":{"current":0,"max":3,"extra":{"value":0,"max":0}}},"gifts":[{"name":"Genius (Part Three Transformation)","description":"**ONLY IN PART THREE:** Hirnloser has realized his intellect is extraordinary. **Tactical Insight:** Once per Scene, Hirnloser can describe a brilliant tactic or strategy that automatically succeeds without requiring a Check. This could be identifying a weakness, setting a perfect ambush, or solving a complex problem instantly. **Countermeasure:** Three times per Scene, Hirnloser can prevent a Hunter from activating a Gift by rapidly explaining how to counter it, neutralizing the advantage. **Prepared:** Hirnloser always has the right tool, item, or piece of information for the current situation, as if he anticipated it. His transformation into The Genius represents validation that his mind was never broken—just different and more advanced than those who judged him.","somaCost":0}],"conditions":[],"specialNotes":"Hirnloser is the truth-teller whose madness makes him hard to understand. In Parts One and Two: speaks only in riddles and rhymes; movements are jerky and unsettling, tilts head at odd angles; stares intensely at things others don't notice; his riddles contain actual truth if decoded (example: 'The scarecrow sees what you cannot. The tin man feels nothing but knows everything. The lion roars but runs away. And the girl with silver shoes walks the yellow road to death' = warning about OZena's path to destruction). If captured by Hunters, he reveals important truths in riddles: 'The wizard in emerald is not what he seems. He steals what he cannot create. The rose blooms red with blood.' In Part Three transformation: speech becomes clear, precise, analytical; shows pride in his intellect; rapidly analyzes situations; no longer rhymes or speaks cryptically. Key moment: when his 'mad' warnings are proven correct, he has breakthrough realization that he was never insane—society just couldn't understand his brilliance. If Hunters show him respect and try to decode his riddles, he becomes more coherent and may help them. If dismissed as 'just crazy,' he becomes hostile, bitter that even in fairy tale world he's not believed. Ultimate fate: may stay in 1780 to become true inventor/scholar or return to revolutionize early 1900s psychiatry with insights about neurodivergent minds."},"_id":"b3c154769331af41"}
{"name":"Lowe the Coward - The Brave Fighter","type":"npc","img":"icons/creatures/mammals/lion-humanoid-roar.webp","system":{"npcType":"creature","oppositionLevel":5,"isMainNPC":true,"background":"Lowe suffers from leontiasis, a rare disease that causes his facial bones to grow abnormally, making his face resemble a lion's. In early 1900s America, he was mocked, feared, and called a coward because he learned to adapt and survive by siding with whoever held power. When Dr. Henkle's Compass Rose malfunctioned and threw them to 1780, Lowe found himself in a world where his appearance was even more terrifying to superstitious villagers. He follows Dorothea (OZena) because she gives him purpose and companionship—she doesn't judge his appearance or his survival tactics. Lowe is actually the most rational of OZena's three companions. He questions her increasingly violent methods but fears abandoning her would mean losing the only family he has. He's not evil—he's pragmatic. He'll side with whoever is winning because that's how he's learned to survive. But deep down, he wishes he had the courage to stand up for what's right rather than what's safe. Throughout the campaign, Lowe undergoes character development. If the Hunters show him kindness and understanding, he begins to question Henkle's manipulation. By Part Three, he can transform into Lowe the Brave Fighter—a lion-faced warrior who has finally found his courage. He becomes immune to fear, inspires allies, and stands firm even when outmatched. His cowardice was never weakness—it was survival. When he finally finds something worth fighting for (whether OZena's redemption or stopping Henkle's madness), he becomes truly heroic. If the Hunters treat him with contempt or violence, he remains hostile and defensive, convinced they're no better than the witch hunters of the 18th century.","descriptors":["I suffer from leontiasis, a disease that makes my face look like a lion's","People call me a coward because I adapt to survive—I'll side with whoever is winning","I just want to belong somewhere and protect those who accept me","I'm more rational than my companions but too afraid to speak up"],"agenda":["Survive and get home to my own time","Protect my companions Dorothea, Hirnloser, and Dose","Avoid unnecessary violence when possible","Find the courage to do what's right instead of what's safe"],"attributes":{"soma":{"current":0,"max":0},"wounds":{"current":0,"max":2,"extra":{"value":0,"max":0}}},"gifts":[{"name":"Hero (Part Three Transformation)","description":"**ONLY IN PART THREE:** Lowe has overcome his cowardice and embraced heroism. **Fearless:** Lowe is immune to all fear effects, intimidation, and mind control attempts. **Inspiring Presence:** Allied NPCs within 30 feet of Lowe gain +1 to their Opposition Level, emboldened by his courage. **Last Stand:** When reduced to 0 Wounds, Lowe can take one final action before falling—a dramatic last strike, final words, or heroic sacrifice. His transformation into The Brave Fighter represents finding something worth fighting for regardless of the odds.","somaCost":0}],"conditions":[],"specialNotes":"Lowe is a tragic figure who represents survival versus heroism. In Parts One and Two, he's conflicted—observes Hunters from distance in Part One to assess if they're threats or potential allies; may negotiate in swamp encounter if Hunters were kind to Henrich and Klaus; attacks alongside OZena in Part Two if she's hostile, but hesitates if shown evidence of Henkle's lies. Voice is hesitant and apologetic initially, becomes more confident in Part Three. Mannerisms: avoids direct eye contact initially, keeps distance, ready to flee; in Part Three stands tall, meets eyes directly, protective stance. Key moment: if Hunters show compassion for his condition rather than disgust, he gains respect for them and is more likely to negotiate or even betray Henkle. If OZena is killed or captured in Part Two and Lowe blames the Hunters, he becomes hostile in Part Three, viewing them as murderers. His ultimate fate: if redeemed, he may stay in 1780 to live boldly or return home to revolutionize treatment of disfigured people; if killed, his last words thank someone for treating him with dignity. Storytellers should emphasize that his 'cowardice' was intelligent survival—he adapted because that's how outcasts survive in cruel worlds."},"_id":"7c3457e408a6073f"}
{"name":"Canine Tigers - Deceptive Guardians","type":"npc","img":"icons/creatures/mammals/dog-hunting-褐色-tan.webp","system":{"npcType":"creature","oppositionLevel":3,"isMainNPC":false,"biography":"Canine Tigers are creatures created by the magical wishing well near Smaragd. They appear as large, friendly dogs—the kind that would greet visitors with wagging tails and playful behavior. This appearance is deceptive. When a Canine Tiger suffers its first wound, it undergoes a horrifying transformation: its Opposition Level skyrockets, it enters a berserker rage, and it becomes fierce as a tiger, attacking the nearest living thing regardless of whether it's ally or enemy. This dual nature makes Canine Tigers particularly dangerous tactical complications. They may initially seem like potential allies or harmless creatures that the Hunters don't need to worry about. Clever enemies might deliberately wound a Canine Tiger to turn it into a threat. Once enraged, a Canine Tiger cannot be reasoned with or calmed—it fights until destroyed or until all nearby creatures flee out of range. The creatures were created by villagers who wished for 'guardians that would never seem threatening,' and the well granted their wish in its typically twisted way: guardians that appear harmless until it's too late. Dr. Henkle uses them strategically throughout Smaragd, positioning them where Hunters might accidentally injure them during other combats.","attributes":{"soma":{"current":0,"max":0},"wounds":{"current":0,"max":2,"extra":{"value":0,"max":1}}},"descriptors":["We appear as large friendly dogs","But we were created by the wishing well to be guardians","We are docile until wounded","Then we become fierce as tigers"],"gifts":[{"name":"Fierce as Tiger","description":"Canine Tigers appear docile and even friendly at first. But when a Canine Tiger suffers its first Wound: **Transformation:** Its Opposition Level immediately increases from 3 to 7. **Berserker Rage:** It enters a rage and attacks the nearest living thing (ally or enemy) without discrimination. **Unstoppable:** It cannot be reasoned with, calmed, or controlled in any way. **Relentless:** It fights until destroyed or until all nearby creatures flee beyond its reach. Storytellers should use Canine Tigers as complications—they may seem harmless until someone accidentally wounds one during another combat."}],"conditions":[],"notes":"Canine Tigers are excellent tactical complications. Place them in combat zones where they might get caught in crossfire. When unwounded, they're OL 3 and friendly-seeming. Once wounded, they become OL 7 berserkers. Henkle uses them strategically—he knows they'll transform and create chaos. Smart Hunters might avoid wounding them or use them tactically by deliberately wounding one near enemies. A wounded Canine Tiger attacking a wish-warped villager might even break the wish's hold temporarily."},"_id":"3a2ff7cd37f24d84"}
{"name":"Manycorpses - The Fused Lovers","type":"npc","img":"icons/magic/unholy/strike-body-explode-disintegrate.webp","system":{"npcType":"creature","oppositionLevel":7,"isMainNPC":true,"biography":"Manycorpses is one of Helga's most terrifying creations—multiple human bodies fused together into one horrifying abomination through blood magic. These were once lovers who came to Helga begging to never be separated. She granted their wish in the cruelest way possible, merging their bodies into a single twisted entity. Now Manycorpses appears as a grotesque amalgamation of limbs, torsos, and heads, all moving in unnatural coordination. It guards Helga's greenhouse on the outskirts of Rot, attacking any intruders on sight. The creature can act twice per Exchange and moves along walls and ceilings like a spider, making it incredibly dangerous in combat. Its multiple voices sometimes speak in unison, expressing the trapped souls' anguish and desire for separation. When killed, Manycorpses speaks with multiple overlapping voices: 'Thank you... we can finally be... separate... at last...' The creature's death is both a mercy and a tragedy—a reminder of Helga's cruelty and the price of desperate wishes.","attributes":{"soma":{"current":0,"max":0},"wounds":{"current":0,"max":4,"extra":{"value":0,"max":1}}},"descriptors":["I am many bodies merged into one through blood magic","I was lovers who begged to never be separated","Now we are together forever, twisted and wrong","Serving the witch who did this to us is our only purpose"],"gifts":[{"name":"Aberration","description":"Manycorpses is a magical aberration with horrifying capabilities. **Act Twice:** Can perform two actions per Exchange instead of one, attacking different targets or performing complex maneuvers. **Wall-Walking:** Can move along walls and ceilings as easily as floors, attacking from unexpected angles and giving defenders 1 Penalty on Defense Checks due to the disorienting assault from above or behind."}],"conditions":[],"notes":"Manycorpses guards the greenhouse containing Wolfgang's alchemical laboratory. Inside are plants for the Infusion of Purity (burdock, nettle, hyssop) but no elderberry. Defeating or bypassing this creature is necessary to access Wolfgang's notes revealing the complete recipe. The creature's multiple limbs allow it to grapple multiple opponents simultaneously, and its wall-crawling ability makes it nearly impossible to corner or trap."},"_id":"dfd289074b45e5a7"}